##* [2 points] Work through the Solved Example section showing progress with each step 1. The PO Box cases tend to have a substring PO.

  1. The regular expression for PO is simply PO.

  2. Find some cases that match:

Addresses <- read_csv("https://mdbeckman.github.io/dcSupplement/data/street-addresses.csv")
Rows: 15483 Columns: 1
 Column specification 
Delimiter: ","
chr (1): address

 Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
 Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
Addresses%>%
  summarise(total=n())
Sample <- 
  Addresses %>%
  sample_n(size = 50)

There are 15483 cases in street name in Wake County, North Carolina.

  1. Find cases that dont match:
Dont <- 
  Sample %>%
  filter( !grepl(pattern = "PO", address))

  1. Find any cases in the Matches that shouldnt be there (none so far in the excerpt shown). Find any cases in Dont that should have matched, for example we want to try and capture the NCSU BOX results among our matches.

  2. It looks like BOX is a better pattern. Since the box number is wanted, the regex should include an identifier for the number inside extraction parentheses. So lets try BOX\s+(\d+)

pattern <- "BOX\\s+(\\d+)"
Matches <- 
  Sample %>% 
  filter(grepl(pattern, address))
Dont <-
  Sample %>%
  filter( !grepl(pattern, address))
Dont
BoxNumbers <- 
  Sample %>%
  filter(grepl(pattern, address)) %>%
  tidyr::extract(address, into = "boxnum", regex = pattern)
BoxNumbers

[2 points] Your Turn #1: explain each line of code in English (either narrative or commented code)

pattern <- "(ST|RD|ROAD)"
LeftOvers <-
  Addresses %>% 
  filter( !grepl(pattern, address),   #use grepl function and pattern format to tidy the data 
          !grepl("\\sAPT|UNIT\\s[\\d]+$", address), # use grepl function to find the format of APT, UNIT and [\\d]
          !grepl(" BOX ", address)    #use grepl function to find the address without "BOX"
          )
LeftOvers

pattern <- (ST|RD|ROAD|CIRCLE|BLVD|CT|TRAIL|LN|AVENUE|BRIDGE|WAY|DRIVE)

Conclusion

Both of medicare and addresses use many circle,road,ST as end identifier. However, medicare uses many RD,TRAIL as identifiers Addresses uses more of BLVD,LN and nearly no AVENUE as identifiers
